body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Run `proc; opt -full; memory_share; dump` on:

```
module top(...);
input [3:0] ra;
output [3:0] rd;
input [3:0] wa1, wa2;
input [3:0] wd1, wd2;
input we, clk;

reg[3:0] mem[0:15];

assign rd = mem[ra];

always @(posedge clk)
        if(we)
                mem[wa1] <= wd1;
        else
                mem[wa2] <= wd2;

endmodule
```

## Expected behavior

The two trivially shareable write ports are merged into one (as happens when `opt -full` is run after `memory_share` instead of before).

## Actual behavior

The ports are not shared — the first port (with `wa1` address) is considered ineligible for merging because its enable is directly wired to module input and does not have a driver.

